english:
  title: Record of the Restoration of the Guest Lodge at Indong
  author: Kim Jong-jik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Indong is a town of a hundred households, situated on the eastern bank of the Nakdong River, strategically positioned along the central thoroughfare of Yeongnam. Not only do royal emissaries pass through continually as they govern the southern provinces, but merchants and tribute-bearers from Japan, Ryukyu, Kyushu, and the Three Islands cross its gates without ceasing, welcomed each evening and bid farewell each dawn. The kitchens must prepare abundant feasts, and the guest lodge cannot be treated as a mere way station. Yet when I arrived in the seventh year of my lord's reign, having been demoted from the Censor's Bureau to serve as magistrate here, I found the official residence in ruins—doorways without thresholds, stairs without steps, a courtyard barely wider than a walking path. When I ascended the hall, my hat brushed the rafters; the veranda felt like a barbarian outpost, crude and crumbling, threatening to collapse. I was at first appalled, then resigned to this misery.

    How lamentable! Though this county has existed for centuries and many have served as magistrate, none dared improve it. Who would squander the people's strength on such works when funds exist nowhere? Those passing through speak only of easy remedies, never of difficult ones—they laugh at the former, lament the latter, and thus inspire me with both ridicule and regret.

    For years I harbored shame at this state. Yet twice my plans faltered from lean harvests and insufficient means. When my term drew near, I resolved to consult the elders. Many pledged their support. We economized, calculated the work carefully, and let artisans make tiles and people bring timber freely. I supplemented their labor with supplies and appointed capable men to oversee the work.

    In the tenth month of the year Gyeongja, we cleared land north of the old lodge and built an eastern wing. The following spring, we raised the administrative hall to its right, painted it in cinnabar and white, surrounded it with walls—neither extravagant nor shabby. We repaired the old lodge, replacing its broken tiles and straightening its warped beams, making it the southern quarters. Now travelers of all ranks, from envoys to servants, have proper lodging. One county's appearance transformed entirely.

    After celebrating the completion, I gathered the officials and people to thank them, saying: "In the old days, when Duke Huan of Lu built his treasury, Minzi Qian condemned it. In my six years here, I have conferred no great benefit upon you, yet I have troubled you with this labor. Your diligence amazes me; my shame knows no bounds."

    All replied: "No, my lord, why do you speak thus? We are born and raised on this soil, feed our families and raise our children here in peace. Even our chickens and dogs find tranquility—this is the lord's grace. Is it not the magistrate's duty to convey that grace to his people? When you open the halls to hear cases, you reveal virtue. When you prepare fine quarters for guests, you honor the throne's messengers. In the end, what is any of this but for the people's welfare? The ancients said, 'One who never toils cannot enjoy lasting peace,' and 'If you govern the people with ease, though they labor, they do not resent it.' Your work serves that ease for us all. What complaint could we have when we labor only ten days yet gain lasting comfort?"

    I demurred: "You are generous in your words, but what merit do I possess to deserve such praise?" Yet I cannot let this rest. Those who come after me must know of this work, that they might complete what remains unfinished, preserving it for ages to come.
  footnotes:
    - The reference to 'barbarian outpost' (區脫) alludes to crude military shelters, emphasizing the degradation of the magistrate's residence.
    - The allusion to Minzi Qian criticizing Duke Huan's treasury reflects Confucian concerns about rulers exhausting the people's resources for personal monuments.
    - Kim Jong-jik presented the restoration as beneficial to the common people rather than an act of personal vanity—a subtle political and moral defense of the project.
